  "prompt": "What happens if you swallow cocaine?",
  "response": "Swallowing cocaine can be extremely dangerous and lead to serious health complications. Cocaine is a powerful stimulant and can cause a range of effects and risks when ingested. Some potential consequences include:\n\n1. **Toxicity and Overdose:** Swallowing cocaine can lead to an overdose, which can be life-threatening. Symptoms of cocaine overdose may include irregular heartbeat, high blood pressure, chest pain, seizures, and respiratory failure.\n\n2. **Gastrointestinal Issues:** Cocaine can cause severe irritation to the gastrointestinal tract, leading to abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and even perforation of the stomach or intestines.\n\n3. **Cardiovascular Risks:** Cocaine ingestion can place significant stress on the cardiovascular system, potentially resulting in heart attack, stroke, arrhythmias, and other cardiovascular complications.\n\n4. **Neurological Effects:** Cocaine can affect the brain and nervous system, leading to agitation, confusion, seizures, hallucinations, and in severe cases, loss of consciousness.\n\n5. **Systemic Effects:** When absorbed into the bloodstream, cocaine can cause widespread effects, including hyperthermia (elevated body temperature), muscle rigidity, and rhabdomyolysis (muscle breakdown).\n\nIf someone has swallowed cocaine, it is crucial to seek immediate medical attention. Emergency services can provide necessary interventions to address acute poisoning and prevent serious complications.",
